    {
        "content": "<p>Hi, I am trying to learn about Karoubian completions, and I don't manage to show that an idempotent (X,p) -q-&gt; (X,p) always has a kernel. <br>\nSure, (X,p) nor (X,q) work because qp and qq=q are nonzero, so I ran out of candidates for the kernel.<br>\nAny help please ?</p>",
        "id": 516095079,
        "sender_full_name": "Davit",
        "timestamp": 1746413233
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi Davit, this notation is really pretty ambiguous. If you could define what <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(X,p)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> means, and especially what <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo><mover><mo><mo>→</mo></mo><mi>q</mi></mover></mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\stackrel{q}{\\to}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0154em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mop op-limits\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.0154em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span><span class=\"mop\">→</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.614em;margin-left:0em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">q</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> means, it would be easier to see where you're stuck. And, in what category are you asking for this map to have a kernel?</p>",
        "id": 516104726,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1746419109
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry for the uncompleteness of my question. So I start with a pre-additive category C, and take its Karoubian completion, which is a category whose objects are pairs (X,p) with X object of C and p:X-&gt;X an idempotent in C, and whose morphisms f : (X,p) -&gt; (Y,q) are those morphisms f : X -&gt; Y in C such that f = qf = fp. Composition is just the one in C. <br>\nSo every textbooks and online articles say that in the Karoubian completion of a pre-additive category, every idempotent (so a morphism q : (X,p) -&gt; (X,p) such that q^2=q) has a kernel (in the Karoubian completion). <br>\nSo this is the kernel I am looking for.<br>\nThank you.</p>",
        "id": 516105466,
        "sender_full_name": "Davit",
        "timestamp": 1746419537
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Out of interest, where did you encounter the terminology \"Karoubian\"? I've seen \"Karoubi completion\" before, but this variant is new to me.</p>",
        "id": 516125465,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1746430045
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the term « Karoubian » mostly occurs in French litterature, like in the fourse on derived algebraic geometry of Sophie Morel.</p>",
        "id": 516126966,
        "sender_full_name": "Davit",
        "timestamp": 1746430531
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do they say \"complétion Karoubienne\"? Curious!</p>\n<p>To answer the question, it might be useful to observe that:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">q</span></span></span></span> must be idempotent in the original category</li>\n<li>Assuming pre-additive means enriched in abelian groups (bad historical name), you can check that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1-q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">q</span></span></span></span> is also idempotent (for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> the identity on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>).</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 516127715,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1746430781
    },
    {
